{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493241"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:01:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:01:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1262"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1262"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.04,0.68,0.21,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110343"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1262"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92615"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2220"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43066"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110343"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of worsening bilateral knee pain. She has a medical history of advanced chronic kidney disease requiring haemodialysis three times weekly, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her medications include lisinopril, insulin, and simvastatin. She does not take any regular medications for bone health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is mild tenderness over both knee joints without effusion or warmth. The remainder of her musculoskeletal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 110 g/L (121-151)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 10 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESodium 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPotassium 4.3 mmol/L (3.5-5.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIonised calcium 0.9 mmol/L (1.05-1.3)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPhosphate 2.5 mmol/L (0.8-1.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrea 16 mmol/L (3.5-9.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine 352 \u03bcmol/L (60-115)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following additional blood tests would be most helpful to determine the cause of her knee pain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum bicarbonate","Serum magnesium","Parathyroid hormone level","Vitamin D level","Serum globulin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with chronic kidney disease presents with bone pain, hypocalcaemia, and hyperphosphataemia, a constellation of findings highly suggestive of secondary hyperparathyroidism. In chronic kidney disease, the kidneys lose their ability to convert 25-hydroxyvitamin D to its active form (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D) and cannot adequately excrete phosphate. The resulting hyperphosphataemia and vitamin D deficiency lead to hypocalcaemia, which stimulates parathyroid hormone secretion. Chronic parathyroid hormone elevation causes increased bone turnover (renal osteodystrophy), presenting as bone pain and increased fracture risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParathyroid hormone level\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next test. It is essential for evaluating any patient with hypocalcaemia and will help confirm the diagnosis of secondary hyperparathyroidism. In this condition, parathyroid hormone levels are elevated despite low calcium levels, as the parathyroid glands attempt to compensate for the hypocalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D level\u003C/strong\u003E measurement could be helpful but is less specific. While vitamin D deficiency contributes to the pathophysiology, the phosphate level helps distinguish this from simple vitamin D deficiency, which typically presents with both low calcium and low phosphate. In this case, the elevated phosphate points more specifically to chronic kidney disease-related mineral bone disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E might be measured if alkalosis were suspected as a cause of hypocalcaemia (through increased calcium-albumin binding), but there is no clinical indication for this in the current presentation, and it would not explain the bone pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum magnesium\u003C/strong\u003E can affect parathyroid hormone secretion and action when severely abnormal, but measuring parathyroid hormone directly is more informative as the primary diagnostic test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum globulin\u003C/strong\u003E elevation might suggest multiple myeloma, but this condition typically presents with hypercalcaemia rather than hypocalcaemia, making it an unlikely diagnosis in this clinical context.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Secondary hyperparathyroidism in chronic kidney disease presents with hypocalcaemia, hyperphosphataemia, and bone pain.","Parathyroid hormone measurement is essential for evaluating the cause of hypocalcaemia.","Chronic kidney disease leads to impaired vitamin D activation and phosphate retention, stimulating parathyroid hormone secretion."],"references":["Stack BC, Secondary Hyperparathyroidism. Otolaryngol Clin North Am. 2024; 57:99-110."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92615"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1262"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92615"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T19:42:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T19:47:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1262"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110343"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"",